Phyllograptus is a graptolite genus of the order Graptoloidea, in the family Phyllograptidae.
Fossils of this genus have been found in the Early Ordovician (475-473 million years ago), in the sediments of Australia, Bolivia, Canada, Chile, China, New Zealand, Norway, Spain, Sweden, the United Kingdom and United States.The normal length of a colony of these leaf-shaped animals could reach a length of 3.5 centimetres (1.4 in). They were passively mobile planktonic suspension feeders.Phyllograptus species are excellent index fossils or guide fossils for identifying Ordovician rocks.